<div class="section">
  <h2>Overview</h2>
  <p>In Scotland, landlords must apply to the <strong>First-tier Tribunal for Scotland (Housing and Property Chamber)</strong> to obtain an eviction order. This is different from England & Wales where you apply to the County Court.</p>

  <div class="important-box">
    <strong>ALL grounds are discretionary in Scotland.</strong> The Tribunal has full discretion to grant or refuse eviction, even if you meet the legal requirements. They will consider the reasonableness of the eviction.
  </div>

  <div class="info-box">
    <strong>No court fees!</strong> Unlike England & Wales, there is no fee to lodge an application with the Scottish Tribunal.
  </div>
</div>

<div class="section">
  <h2>Before You Apply</h2>

  <h3>Pre-Action Requirements (Rent Arrears)</h3>
  <p>If you are seeking eviction for rent arrears (Ground 1), you <strong>MUST</strong> complete pre-action requirements:</p>
  <ul class="checklist">
    <li>Contact the tenant about the arrears</li>
    <li>Provide clear information about the arrears amount</li>
    <li>Signpost tenant to debt advice services</li>
    <li>Attempt to agree a repayment plan</li>
    <li>Wait at least 14 days after completing pre-action steps</li>
  </ul>

  <div class="warning-box">
    The Tribunal will ask for evidence of pre-action compliance. Applications without this evidence will likely be rejected or delayed.
  </div>

  <h3>Notice to Leave</h3>
  <p>Before applying, you must have served a valid Notice to Leave with the correct notice period:</p>
  <table>
    <tr>
      <th>Ground</th>
      <th>Notice Period</th>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td>Ground 1 (arrears at notice date)</td>
      <td>28 days</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td>Ground 3 (anti-social behaviour)</td>
      <td>28 days</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td>Ground 4 (landlord to occupy)</td>
      <td>84 days</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td>Ground 5 (sale of property)</td>
      <td>84 days</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td>Other grounds</td>
      <td>28 or 84 days (varies)</td>
    </tr>
  </table>
</div>

<div class="section">
  <h2>How to Lodge Your Application</h2>

  <p>Applications are made online through the Tribunal's portal.</p>

  <div class="step-box">
    <p><span class="step-number">1</span> <strong>Go to the Tribunal Portal</strong></p>
    <p>Visit: <em>www.housingandpropertychamber.scot</em></p>
    <p>Click "Make an Application" or "Lodge an Application"</p>
  </div>

  <div class="step-box">
    <p><span class="step-number">2</span> <strong>Select the correct application type</strong></p>
    <p>For eviction, select:</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>"Application for an eviction order"</strong> (Private Residential Tenancy)</li>
    </ul>
  </div>

  <div class="step-box">
    <p><span class="step-number">3</span> <strong>Complete the application form</strong></p>
    <p>You'll need to provide:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>Your details (landlord/applicant)</li>
      <li>Tenant details (respondent)</li>
      <li>Property address</li>
      <li>Tenancy start date</li>
      <li>Ground(s) for eviction</li>
      <li>Details supporting your grounds</li>
    </ul>
  </div>

  <div class="step-box">
    <p><span class="step-number">4</span> <strong>Upload supporting documents</strong></p>
    <p>Required documents:</p>
    <ul class="checklist">
      <li>Copy of the tenancy agreement</li>
      <li>Copy of Notice to Leave (and proof of service)</li>
      <li>Rent statement / arrears schedule (if arrears ground)</li>
      <li>Pre-action protocol evidence (if arrears ground)</li>
      <li>Any other evidence supporting your grounds</li>
    </ul>
  </div>

  <div class="step-box">
    <p><span class="step-number">5</span> <strong>Submit the application</strong></p>
    <p>Review and submit. You'll receive a confirmation and reference number.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="success-box">
    <strong>No fee required!</strong> The Scottish Tribunal does not charge application fees for housing cases.
  </div>
</div>

<div class="section">
  <h2>What Happens After You Lodge</h2>

  <h3>Timeline (Typical)</h3>
  <ol>
    <li><strong>Acknowledgement</strong> - Within 1-2 weeks of lodging</li>
    <li><strong>Acceptance</strong> - Tribunal checks application is valid (2-4 weeks)</li>
    <li><strong>Service on tenant</strong> - Tribunal serves papers on tenant</li>
    <li><strong>Response period</strong> - Tenant has 14 days to respond</li>
    <li><strong>Case Management Discussion (CMD)</strong> - Usually 4-8 weeks after lodging</li>
    <li><strong>Full Hearing</strong> - If required, 2-4 weeks after CMD</li>
    <li><strong>Decision</strong> - Usually issued 1-2 weeks after hearing</li>
  </ol>

  <h3>Case Management Discussion (CMD)</h3>
  <p>This is a preliminary hearing (usually by phone or video call) where the Tribunal:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>Checks both parties understand the process</li>
    <li>Identifies the issues to be decided</li>
    <li>May make a decision if the case is straightforward</li>
    <li>Schedules a full hearing if needed</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Full Hearing</h3>
  <p>If a full hearing is required, you will:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>Present your evidence</li>
    <li>Answer questions from the Tribunal</li>
    <li>The tenant can present their case</li>
    <li>The Tribunal makes a decision</li>
  </ul>
</div>

<div class="section">
  <h2>After the Eviction Order</h2>

  <p>If the Tribunal grants an eviction order:</p>

  <div class="step-box">
    <p><span class="step-number">1</span> <strong>Wait for the order to take effect</strong></p>
    <p>The order usually gives the tenant time to leave (often 14-28 days).</p>
  </div>

  <div class="step-box">
    <p><span class="step-number">2</span> <strong>If tenant doesn't leave - apply for enforcement</strong></p>
    <p>Apply to Sheriff Officers (not bailiffs) for enforcement of the order.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="step-box">
    <p><span class="step-number">3</span> <strong>Sheriff Officers enforce the order</strong></p>
    <p>They will attend the property and require the tenant to leave.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="warning-box">
    <strong>Never attempt self-help eviction!</strong> It is a criminal offence in Scotland to evict a tenant without a Tribunal order.
  </div>
</div>

<div class="section">
  <h2>Ground-Specific Requirements</h2>

  <h3>Ground 1 - Rent Arrears</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>At least 3 months' rent must be outstanding</li>
    <li>Pre-action protocol must be completed</li>
    <li>Arrears must exist at both notice date AND hearing date</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Ground 4 - Landlord Intends to Occupy</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>You must genuinely intend to live in the property</li>
    <li>You must not re-let the property within 3 months</li>
    <li>Penalty of up to 6 months' rent if you misuse this ground</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Ground 5 - Sale of Property</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>You must genuinely intend to sell</li>
    <li>Property must be marketed for sale</li>
    <li>Penalty of up to 6 months' rent if you don't sell</li>
  </ul>
</div>

